00:39:55.770 --> 00:39:59.770
One is get three times
interrupted more often

00:39:59.770 --> 00:40:02.885
and another is that you include
women in your congregation

00:40:02.885 --> 00:40:06.460
or gathering so decision
making you have some result?

00:40:06.460 --> 00:40:08.030
The second one I
don't follow you on.

00:40:08.030 --> 00:40:09.613
GEMMA MUNRO: [INAUDIBLE]
I understand.

00:40:09.613 --> 00:40:13.510
So in terms of results
in individual performance

00:40:13.510 --> 00:40:17.880
in a mixed leadership program
versus a women-only leadership

00:40:17.880 --> 00:40:20.590
program, you get
three to one results

00:40:20.590 --> 00:40:22.590
with a women's leadership
program for women.

00:40:22.590 --> 00:40:24.330
Obviously, don't put men in
a women's leadership program,

00:40:24.330 --> 00:40:26.240
because that would perhaps be
a little bit weird for them.

00:40:26.240 --> 00:40:28.920
But the women who go on a
women-only leadership program

00:40:28.920 --> 00:40:31.017
achieve three to
one results in terms

00:40:31.017 --> 00:40:32.850
of getting promoted,
in terms of performance

00:40:32.850 --> 00:40:36.400
ratings from their peers
and their executives.

00:40:36.400 --> 00:40:38.320
Does that make sense?

00:40:38.320 --> 00:40:41.660
So women-only programs
for women are more

00:40:41.660 --> 00:40:43.769
effective than mixed programs.

00:40:43.769 --> 00:40:46.310
We've got a white paper on it
if anyone wants me to share it.

00:40:46.310 --> 00:40:49.718
I'm happy to Just email me.

00:40:49.718 --> 00:40:50.520
Other questions?

00:40:54.340 --> 00:40:56.000
AUDIENCE: Do you
have tips for how

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:57.790
to handle being interrupted?

00:40:57.790 --> 00:40:59.020
GEMMA MUNRO: Yes, I do.

00:40:59.020 --> 00:41:00.625
I get asked this
question so much,

00:41:00.625 --> 00:41:03.060
I actually made a video on
it, how to insert yourself

00:41:03.060 --> 00:41:04.350
into the conversation.

00:41:04.350 --> 00:41:06.816
But I'll share a couple
of them with you today.

00:41:06.816 --> 00:41:08.690
If you want to email
me, I'm happy to forward

00:41:08.690 --> 00:41:10.430
you that video.

00:41:10.430 --> 00:41:13.020
One is the broken
record technique.

00:41:13.020 --> 00:41:15.240
So you just keep
saying the same thing.

00:41:15.240 --> 00:41:18.040
So what I think on this is,
so what I think on this is,

00:41:18.040 --> 00:41:19.380
so what I think on this is.

00:41:19.380 --> 00:41:23.370
You feel like an idiot, but
it did eventually works.

00:41:23.370 --> 00:41:25.460
Another thing is to
actually call it,

00:41:25.460 --> 00:41:27.270
but when you call
the interruption,

00:41:27.270 --> 00:41:31.080
you need to make sure
there's no emotion involved.

00:41:31.080 --> 00:41:32.725
So what I think
is-- Kevin, can you

00:41:32.725 --> 00:41:33.560
let me finish what I'm saying?

00:41:33.560 --> 00:41:34.890
It's always Kev-- I
always call guys Kevin.

00:41:34.890 --> 00:41:35.598
I don't know why.

00:41:37.825 --> 00:41:39.700
Kevin, can you let me
finish what I'm saying?

00:41:39.700 --> 00:41:43.480
And actually call it there
in a really calm way.

00:41:43.480 --> 00:41:47.440
And the third thing is, if
you've tried one and two

00:41:47.440 --> 00:41:51.080
and neither of them work,
let them have their rant,

00:41:51.080 --> 00:41:53.280
because often it's a rant.

00:41:53.280 --> 00:41:55.820
And then at the end,
summarize what they've said.

00:41:55.820 --> 00:41:57.780
So Kevin, what I've
heard is bop bop bop.

00:41:57.780 --> 00:41:58.499
Here's my view.

00:41:58.499 --> 00:42:00.040
And if you do that,
you actually tend

00:42:00.040 --> 00:42:01.960
to sound like the smartest
person in the room.

00:42:04.820 --> 00:42:05.320
Yeah.

00:42:05.320 --> 00:42:08.320
I'll just [INAUDIBLE] the
mic if that's all right?

00:42:08.320 --> 00:42:11.100
AUDIENCE: So any tip on--
so what if your manager

00:42:11.100 --> 00:42:14.440
wants you to sit on the back
seat instead of a leader?

00:42:14.440 --> 00:42:15.150
And what if he--

00:42:15.150 --> 00:42:16.090
GEMMA MUNRO: What seat, sorry?

00:42:16.090 --> 00:42:16.880
AUDIENCE: Back seat.

00:42:16.880 --> 00:42:17.838
GEMMA MUNRO: Back seat.

00:42:17.838 --> 00:42:18.620
Got it, sorry.

00:42:18.620 --> 00:42:20.036
AUDIENCE: And what
if he wants you

00:42:20.036 --> 00:42:23.090
to-- the same
solution and problem.

00:42:23.090 --> 00:42:25.850
He'd rather listen to a
man than listen to you.

00:42:25.850 --> 00:42:27.600
So you have to go
through a second channel

00:42:27.600 --> 00:42:29.200
in order to convey the message.

00:42:29.200 --> 00:42:30.720
GEMMA MUNRO: Yes.

00:42:30.720 --> 00:42:35.910
That's really difficult.
Before I give you a tip,

00:42:35.910 --> 00:42:38.396
I've noticed there
is almost-- and I

00:42:38.396 --> 00:42:40.270
don't know your situation,
of course, at all.

00:42:40.270 --> 00:42:43.264
But I have noticed there's
almost this discrimination

00:42:43.264 --> 00:42:45.180
that in some ways it's
reverse discrimination.

00:42:45.180 --> 00:42:51.770
I see some men have kind of a
caring patronizing sense of,

00:42:51.770 --> 00:42:53.885
oh, that would be
too hard for you.

00:42:53.885 --> 00:42:55.760
Like I don't want to
put you in the deep end,

00:42:55.760 --> 00:42:57.330
and they do this for women.

00:42:57.330 --> 00:43:00.590
And I honestly had this
male exec come and talk

00:43:00.590 --> 00:43:03.080
to these women that we're
running a program with,

00:43:03.080 --> 00:43:04.680
and he talked about
his story and how

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:06.570
he was crying at nights,
and he was vomiting

00:43:06.570 --> 00:43:07.780
because it was horrible.

00:43:07.780 --> 00:43:10.470
But he's so glad he went through
that because now he's here.

00:43:10.470 --> 00:43:13.690
And then he left the room,
and these women said to me,

00:43:13.690 --> 00:43:15.470
they don't do that to me.

00:43:15.470 --> 00:43:17.589
He won't give me
those opportunities,

00:43:17.589 --> 00:43:19.130
because he's looking
after me, and he

00:43:19.130 --> 00:43:21.090
wants me to be protected.

00:43:21.090 --> 00:43:22.560
So we've got to watch that.

00:43:22.560 --> 00:43:25.809
In terms of actually
managing that,

00:43:25.809 --> 00:43:27.850
I'm hesitant to give you
a tip, because it really

00:43:27.850 --> 00:43:32.750
depends on the personality
of the guy involved.

00:43:32.750 --> 00:43:36.358
Have you had a conversation
with him about it?

00:43:36.358 --> 00:43:37.640
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:43:37.640 --> 00:43:38.830
Observe and learn.

00:43:38.830 --> 00:43:40.840
GEMMA MUNRO: Observe and learn?

00:43:40.840 --> 00:43:41.970
Yeah?

00:43:41.970 --> 00:43:46.352
So I'm wondering if-- again,
it depends on the person.

00:43:46.352 --> 00:43:50.970
I don't want to give you advice
that could get you fired.

00:43:50.970 --> 00:43:54.520
So you know, that
caveat in place.

00:43:54.520 --> 00:43:56.660
I found what works
the best is actually

00:43:56.660 --> 00:44:01.110
calling that and saying,
here's my perception.

00:44:01.110 --> 00:44:03.650
Please tell me if I'm wrong.

00:44:03.650 --> 00:44:06.310
My sense is you don't want
me to move into a leadership

00:44:06.310 --> 00:44:09.160
position, and you're quite
happy for me to stay here.

00:44:09.160 --> 00:44:11.580
I do want to move into
a leadership position.

00:44:11.580 --> 00:44:13.170
So can we have
that conversation?

00:44:13.170 --> 00:44:15.830
And, again, no aggression there.

00:44:15.830 --> 00:44:17.460
There's no emotion.

00:44:17.460 --> 00:44:20.030
It's just stating as it is
in a really factual way.

00:44:20.030 --> 00:44:22.050
I've done that before two guys.

00:44:22.050 --> 00:44:24.730
I've called two guys
out for sexist behavior,

00:44:24.730 --> 00:44:29.300
and they actually tend
to go, oh, I had no idea.

00:44:29.300 --> 00:44:30.790
So that would be my suggestion.

00:44:30.790 --> 00:44:32.742
No worries.

00:44:32.742 --> 00:44:33.720
Other questions.

00:44:38.457 --> 00:44:39.290
We will come to you.

00:44:44.460 --> 00:44:47.070
AUDIENCE: Sometimes I
get comments from people

00:44:47.070 --> 00:44:50.170
that I don't really
know what to make of,

00:44:50.170 --> 00:44:51.580
and they're nice people.

00:44:51.580 --> 00:44:55.730
But they'll say that
women, in general,

00:44:55.730 --> 00:44:58.580
might have an easier time,
let's say, finding a job in tech

00:44:58.580 --> 00:45:02.680
because there's been all
this attention to equality,

00:45:02.680 --> 00:45:05.840
and there's just a lack
of women applicants.

00:45:05.840 --> 00:45:08.155
And then they'll make
it sound like, oh yeah,

00:45:08.155 --> 00:45:10.530
you got your job because your
a girl-- like a little bit,

00:45:10.530 --> 00:45:13.370
not too much, but a little bit.

00:45:13.370 --> 00:45:15.470
How can I deal with that?

00:45:15.470 --> 00:45:16.220
GEMMA MUNRO: Yeah.

00:45:16.220 --> 00:45:17.500
That is such a good question.

00:45:17.500 --> 00:45:19.540
And, again, it depends on
the kind of person you are

00:45:19.540 --> 00:45:21.414
and how much you feel
like you could get away

00:45:21.414 --> 00:45:22.440
with in the situation.

00:45:22.440 --> 00:45:25.330
But I've been known to say
to people who have insinuated

00:45:25.330 --> 00:45:27.740
that, to say, have you ever
thought that maybe you're

00:45:27.740 --> 00:45:29.967
here because you're a guy?

00:45:29.967 --> 00:45:31.550
So maybe you're in
the position you're

00:45:31.550 --> 00:45:38.240
at-- we've had generations
where male leaders have

00:45:38.240 --> 00:45:39.210
been advantage.

00:45:39.210 --> 00:45:41.220
Have you ever thought
the you are here simply

00:45:41.220 --> 00:45:42.720
because of your gender?

00:45:42.720 --> 00:45:45.450
And that tends to shut
them up pretty quickly.

00:45:45.450 --> 00:45:49.359
But that does require
a little bit of oh-ah.

00:45:49.359 --> 00:45:50.900
There's a good word
for that, but I'm

00:45:50.900 --> 00:45:52.649
sure it's rude so I'm
not going to use it.

00:45:52.649 --> 00:45:55.610
It does require some encourage.

00:45:55.610 --> 00:45:57.576
If not, I actually
think just calling that

00:45:57.576 --> 00:45:58.950
and actually asking
the question.

00:45:58.950 --> 00:46:01.220
Again, in completely
non-emotional way,

00:46:01.220 --> 00:46:03.470
are you saying that I'm here
just because I'm a woman?

00:46:03.470 --> 00:46:04.914
I'm not smart enough to be here?

00:46:04.914 --> 00:46:07.330
And you watch them retreat
back from that position really,

00:46:07.330 --> 00:46:07.955
really quickly.

00:46:12.889 --> 00:46:14.805
AUDIENCE: I had a question
about making space.

00:46:14.805 --> 00:46:15.750
GEMMA MUNRO: Yes.

00:46:15.750 --> 00:46:18.060
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
that in meetings, especially

