in business, there
can be a culture

00:46:20.290 --> 00:46:21.830
within the meeting
or a tone that's

00:46:21.830 --> 00:46:24.960
combative or masculine and loud.

00:46:24.960 --> 00:46:27.040
I'm wondering what the
characteristics are

00:46:27.040 --> 00:46:28.880
of a feminine tone
in meetings and also

00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:31.560
if there are any leaders or
forums that you could point me

00:46:31.560 --> 00:46:32.060
to.

00:46:32.060 --> 00:46:34.070
Because when I'm
thinking of examples,

00:46:34.070 --> 00:46:37.730
I think whether it's politics
or sports or television shows,

00:46:37.730 --> 00:46:38.420
it's everywhere.

00:46:38.420 --> 00:46:40.940
It's loud, and it's in your
face, and it's combative.

00:46:40.940 --> 00:46:43.610
And so what are examples
of the other side?

00:46:43.610 --> 00:46:44.800
GEMMA MUNRO: Absolutely.

00:46:44.800 --> 00:46:46.090
I love that question.

00:46:46.090 --> 00:46:49.380
Actually, when I was working
in this consultancy that did

00:46:49.380 --> 00:46:51.930
have this masculine
tennis match style,

00:46:51.930 --> 00:46:54.710
and I was really
feeling that pressure

00:46:54.710 --> 00:46:56.680
to be other than who I was.

00:46:56.680 --> 00:46:59.540
At the same time, I started
working with this male project

00:46:59.540 --> 00:47:02.690
director who had quite a
feminine style of conversation.

00:47:02.690 --> 00:47:05.850
And it actually
felt like ideas were

00:47:05.850 --> 00:47:09.490
allowed to blossom rather
than shut down, shut down.

00:47:09.490 --> 00:47:13.300
So stupid ideas were
allowed to percolate.

00:47:13.300 --> 00:47:17.540
Ideas that were
raised were given--

00:47:17.540 --> 00:47:20.050
what's the word-- were
actually acknowledged,

00:47:20.050 --> 00:47:22.040
we're given acknowledgement.

00:47:22.040 --> 00:47:27.780
And a more feminine style, there
is a sense of yes and rather

00:47:27.780 --> 00:47:28.970
than no but.

00:47:28.970 --> 00:47:30.720
Yes and.

00:47:30.720 --> 00:47:33.560
In terms of examples, can
you leave that with me,

00:47:33.560 --> 00:47:35.302
and can I get your
details afterwards?

00:47:35.302 --> 00:47:37.260
That's a really good
question, and I don't have

00:47:37.260 --> 00:47:39.080
anyone springing to mind sadly.

00:47:39.080 --> 00:47:41.130
So I'd love to email
you some examples

00:47:41.130 --> 00:47:43.217
once I've given it some thought.

00:47:43.217 --> 00:47:45.550
AUDIENCE: Let's do a question
from the Dory really fast.

00:47:45.550 --> 00:47:48.680
So when you think about some
of the best leaders you've

00:47:48.680 --> 00:47:50.550
observed slash
worked with, what are

00:47:50.550 --> 00:47:52.650
some of the characteristics
or behaviors

00:47:52.650 --> 00:47:54.660
they have that make them great?

00:47:54.660 --> 00:47:56.170
GEMMA MUNRO: Yeah.

00:47:56.170 --> 00:47:59.370
There's actually some
research done by Gallup.

00:47:59.370 --> 00:48:03.560
And the research was
done on 10,000 followers

00:48:03.560 --> 00:48:05.800
and looking at what
these followers needed

00:48:05.800 --> 00:48:07.220
from their leaders.

00:48:07.220 --> 00:48:08.870
And I know this
research, and I also

00:48:08.870 --> 00:48:11.790
know the leaders I've worked
with that I have responded best

00:48:11.790 --> 00:48:13.850
to, and they do it align.

00:48:13.850 --> 00:48:16.870
So the Gallup research
says that followers require

00:48:16.870 --> 00:48:20.670
leaders to provide stability.

00:48:20.670 --> 00:48:23.420
So I don't know if you've
ever had a leader where

00:48:23.420 --> 00:48:26.426
you never quite know what you're
going to get on a certain day.

00:48:26.426 --> 00:48:29.050
And some days it's like, oh, is
it going to be eggshells today?

00:48:29.050 --> 00:48:31.690
And you're kind of tentatively
walking into the office.

00:48:31.690 --> 00:48:33.700
Providing a sense of
stability is important.

00:48:33.700 --> 00:48:35.230
Creating hope.

00:48:35.230 --> 00:48:37.999
Creating a sense of here's
what the future looks like.

00:48:37.999 --> 00:48:39.790
And it's going to be
incredible, and here's

00:48:39.790 --> 00:48:41.940
how we're going to
get there together.

00:48:41.940 --> 00:48:45.260
Showing compassion is another
one that's really important

00:48:45.260 --> 00:48:46.880
and building trust.

00:48:46.880 --> 00:48:50.450
If you as a leader can
do those four things,

00:48:50.450 --> 00:48:51.760
then followers respond.

00:48:51.760 --> 00:48:54.343
And I've certainly had leaders
that have been able to do that.

00:48:58.910 --> 00:49:00.910
AUDIENCE: A common
criticism of leading advice

00:49:00.910 --> 00:49:02.720
is that it places
the burden on women

00:49:02.720 --> 00:49:05.350
to deal with the
consequences of a system not

00:49:05.350 --> 00:49:06.670
of their own making.

00:49:06.670 --> 00:49:08.960
How can organizations
help redirect

00:49:08.960 --> 00:49:12.720
that burden to be even
more evenly shared?

00:49:12.720 --> 00:49:14.386
GEMMA MUNRO: I just
want to say, whoever

00:49:14.386 --> 00:49:17.560
asked that, I love that
question, because it's so true.

00:49:17.560 --> 00:49:20.570
We were pitching
for this program

00:49:20.570 --> 00:49:26.510
with 10 high-potential women
in a car sales organization

00:49:26.510 --> 00:49:30.840
and where the top 50
leaders were male.

00:49:30.840 --> 00:49:33.370
No female in the top
50 level leaders.

00:49:33.370 --> 00:49:35.640
And one of their
aims for this program

00:49:35.640 --> 00:49:38.040
was at the end of
the program, women

00:49:38.040 --> 00:49:39.550
will able to champion
gender equity

00:49:39.550 --> 00:49:41.800
and change the culture
in the organization.

00:49:41.800 --> 00:49:46.540
You are putting that burden on
10 women in the organization.

00:49:46.540 --> 00:49:48.550
So for me, it's
incredibly important

00:49:48.550 --> 00:49:52.177
that, yes, we need to
make sure that women

00:49:52.177 --> 00:49:54.760
have the confidence and skills
to navigate an environment that

00:49:54.760 --> 00:49:58.020
is less than ideal
for some women.

00:49:58.020 --> 00:50:00.850
At the same time though, you
cannot do that without working

00:50:00.850 --> 00:50:05.280
with the organization's leaders
to help them get it and to give

00:50:05.280 --> 00:50:07.910
them the skills to help these
women who are actually being

00:50:07.910 --> 00:50:09.210
developed to thrive.

00:50:09.210 --> 00:50:12.210
So to me, it always has
to be that joint approach.

00:50:12.210 --> 00:50:13.940
And what you're
looking for in the end

00:50:13.940 --> 00:50:18.100
is you're wanting women to climb
up through the leadership path

00:50:18.100 --> 00:50:19.990
to become leaders
in the organization

00:50:19.990 --> 00:50:22.304
and eventually to have
enough critical mass there

00:50:22.304 --> 00:50:24.345
to shape how work gets
done in that organization.

00:50:27.889 --> 00:50:29.680
AUDIENCE: You were
mentioning the gentleman

00:50:29.680 --> 00:50:32.720
at the cafe who had an
opinion about what you do.

00:50:32.720 --> 00:50:34.720
So I'm just wondering
what he had to say or just

00:50:34.720 --> 00:50:37.682
generally what do
the skeptics say?

00:50:37.682 --> 00:50:38.390
GEMMA MUNRO: Yes.

00:50:38.390 --> 00:50:39.660
OK.

00:50:39.660 --> 00:50:44.430
His view was, well, you
just-- I have this male voice.

00:50:44.430 --> 00:50:45.990
I know men don't
all talk like this,

00:50:45.990 --> 00:50:47.720
but he was quite blustery.

00:50:47.720 --> 00:50:51.154
Well, I get women
and I'm able to tell

00:50:51.154 --> 00:50:53.320
the men in my organization
what they're doing wrong,

00:50:53.320 --> 00:50:54.340
and I say that to
women, and they

00:50:54.340 --> 00:50:56.250
say you're just saying
that because I'm a woman.

00:50:56.250 --> 00:50:58.333
And they've just got a big
chip on their shoulder.

00:50:58.333 --> 00:51:00.890
And at that point, I
started to switch off a bit,

00:51:00.890 --> 00:51:02.274
but I actually did fight back.

00:51:02.274 --> 00:51:03.690
You tend to get a
number of-- it's

00:51:03.690 --> 00:51:05.065
a really good
question-- you tend

00:51:05.065 --> 00:51:07.620
to get a number of common
reactions from people.

00:51:07.620 --> 00:51:10.990
One is I think the
issue is overstated.

00:51:10.990 --> 00:51:14.150
One is women don't need fixing.

00:51:14.150 --> 00:51:16.350
And actually I do
have a video that I

00:51:16.350 --> 00:51:19.220
made on how to respond
to the common reactions--

00:51:19.220 --> 00:51:22.380
the common negative reactions
to gender diversity.

00:51:22.380 --> 00:51:24.208
So if anyone wants
that, just let me know,

00:51:24.208 --> 00:51:24.650
I'm happy to share.

00:51:24.650 --> 00:51:26.520
I think I went through
six common reactions,

00:51:26.520 --> 00:51:27.686
and here's what you can say.

00:51:33.010 --> 00:51:34.850
AUDIENCE: So usually
the behaviors--

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:38.720
the measured behavior, right--
so if you're working with a lot

00:51:38.720 --> 00:51:43.140
of men and not women, you
tend to become-- you know,

00:51:43.140 --> 00:51:46.000
to survive, you want to
become like them a little bit

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:48.100
to be able to work with them.

00:51:48.100 --> 00:51:50.000
But maybe you don't like that.

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:52.640
Maybe end of the day, you
don't want to be like that.

00:51:52.640 --> 00:51:56.010
And so that's very
conflicting kind of feeling.

00:51:56.010 --> 00:51:56.990
You do it.

00:51:56.990 --> 00:51:59.340
Maybe it works,
but end of the day,

00:51:59.340 --> 00:52:01.340
you don't want to be like that.

00:52:01.340 --> 00:52:02.960
GEMMA MUNRO: Absolutely.

00:52:02.960 --> 00:52:05.540
And it's actually natural.

00:52:05.540 --> 00:52:08.700
Albert Bandura has this
social learning theory--

00:52:08.700 --> 00:52:11.500
we learn by imitating others
and by mimicking others.

00:52:11.500 --> 00:52:13.430
And if the dominant
leadership style

00:52:13.430 --> 00:52:16.050
has been masculine, competitive,
hierarchical, et cetera,

00:52:16.050 --> 00:52:18.860
that's what we tend to learn
we need to do to be successful.

00:52:18.860 --> 00:52:20.230
Is a survival thing.

00:52:20.230 --> 00:52:23.770
We imitate so that we can
survive in a certain situation.

00:52:23.770 --> 00:52:25.660
At the same time
though, there can

00:52:25.660 --> 00:52:28.930
be a sense of
inauthenticity and feeling

00:52:28.930 --> 00:52:30.690
like I'm not being
exactly who I am.

00:52:30.690 --> 00:52:32.780
And that feels icky too.

00:52:32.780 --> 00:52:34.480
So you have hit the
nail on the head.

00:52:34.480 --> 00:52:36.039
You are absolutely right.

00:52:36.039 --> 00:52:38.080
One thing I suggest to
people who find themselves

00:52:38.080 --> 00:52:40.730
in this situation, and it's
men and women too, by the way.

00:52:40.730 --> 00:52:43.160
I was working with an
all-male executive team,

00:52:43.160 --> 00:52:47.804
and the CEO said to me, well--
I was about to say his name.

00:52:47.804 --> 00:52:49.845
Let's say he's called
Kevin, because as you know,

00:52:49.845 --> 00:52:51.439
I call all men Kevin.

00:52:51.439 --> 00:52:52.855
Well, Kevin, you
know, he's great.

00:52:52.855 --> 00:52:54.996
He's performing well,
but he can't fit in.

00:52:54.996 --> 00:52:55.745
He's a vegetarian.

00:52:55.745 --> 00:52:56.750
He doesn't eat sausages.

00:52:56.750 --> 00:52:57.458
He doesn't drink.

00:52:57.458 --> 00:52:59.000
I'm like, oh my god.

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:02.396
How inclusive are not
being at the moment?

00:53:02.396 --> 00:53:04.270
What I suggest to men
and women who feel like

00:53:04.270 --> 00:53:06.880
they're in a situation where
they cannot be themselves is

00:53:06.880 --> 00:53:09.570
to start making little tweaks.

00:53:09.570 --> 00:53:11.445
So not suddenly coming
into work as yourself,

00:53:11.445 --> 00:53:13.236
because that's going
to feel way too scary,

00:53:13.236 --> 00:53:15.550
and your colleagues will go--
they'll sort of whiplash.

00:53:15.550 --> 00:53:16.049
Who are you?

00:53:16.049 --> 00:53:17.950
I don't really
trust you anymore.

00:53:17.950 --> 00:53:20.190
But making little tweaks,
just planning a little

00:53:20.190 --> 00:53:22.784
tweak you can make to be
more yourself at work.

00:53:22.784 --> 00:53:24.950
Some of them you actually
find, actually this great.

00:53:24.950 --> 00:53:26.860
People respond to be better.

00:53:26.860 --> 00:53:28.584
So just build that up.

00:53:28.584 --> 00:53:31.000
Eventually, if you feel like
you're trying to be yourself,

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.260
and it doesn't work in
this environment, that's

00:53:33.260 --> 00:53:34.850
when you need to
start thinking, well,

00:53:34.850 --> 00:53:36.200
is this the right
environment for me?

00:53:36.200 --> 00:53:38.074
Do I need to find an
environment where I feel

00:53:38.074 --> 00:53:40.696
like I can be truly who I am.

00:53:40.696 --> 00:53:42.570
AUDIENCE: We have time
for one more question.

00:53:42.570 --> 00:53:43.320
GEMMA MUNRO: Yeah.

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:47.500
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
from the Dory.

00:53:47.500 --> 00:53:49.540
So bravado versus bravery.

00:53:49.540 --> 00:53:52.280
A lot of leaders have
this fake it 'til make it

00:53:52.280 --> 00:53:54.140
bluster and pretense
way of leading

00:53:54.140 --> 00:53:57.720
but may not always have
your back when it counts.

00:53:57.720 --> 00:54:02.160
What are the attributes of
a truly brave change maker?

00:54:02.160 --> 00:54:05.200
GEMMA MUNRO: What
a great question.

00:54:05.200 --> 00:54:07.940
I ironically think the
attributes of someone

00:54:07.940 --> 00:54:12.260
who's brave and who's changing
the way things get done,

00:54:12.260 --> 00:54:15.380
one of the attributes is
absolutely vulnerability.

00:54:15.380 --> 00:54:18.420
So bravado, for me, is
look how great I am.

00:54:18.420 --> 00:54:20.760
Look what I can do.

00:54:20.760 --> 00:54:22.977
There is that sense
of bluster about it.

00:54:22.977 --> 00:54:24.560
Having said that, I
do think sometimes

00:54:24.560 --> 00:54:26.150
you have to fake it
until you make it.

00:54:26.150 --> 00:54:28.710
But if you are doing
that and at the same time

00:54:28.710 --> 00:54:32.400
you're not being honest and open
with others about where you're

00:54:32.400 --> 00:54:35.540
struggling, being honest
and open with others

00:54:35.540 --> 00:54:37.620
and being vulnerable
and actually

00:54:37.620 --> 00:54:41.900
having that sense
of here's who I am,

00:54:41.900 --> 00:54:45.770
you don't tend to be respected
by those who follow you.

00:54:45.770 --> 00:54:48.950
We actually follow people
who show us who they are.

00:54:48.950 --> 00:54:52.270
And that requires opening
themselves up and telling

00:54:52.270 --> 00:54:55.150
people what they are
afraid of and giving people

00:54:55.150 --> 00:54:56.610
a sense of this
is where we're at.

00:54:56.610 --> 00:54:57.568
These are the problems.

00:54:57.568 --> 00:55:00.540
I am really nervous, and
yet I see this fabulous goal

00:55:00.540 --> 00:55:01.350
for the future.

00:55:01.350 --> 00:55:03.183
And here's how we're
going to work together.

00:55:03.183 --> 00:55:07.210
I think the other attribute--
so bravado tends to be me me me.

00:55:07.210 --> 00:55:10.200
Brave tends to be let's
bring people along.

00:55:10.200 --> 00:55:12.670
So it's not about me,
it is about this team

00:55:12.670 --> 00:55:15.880
and creating results as a team.

00:55:15.880 --> 00:55:17.230
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:55:17.230 --> 00:55:19.980
[APPLAUSE]

